name: 4-fluoro-2-methylphenol

name: 4-fluoro-2-methylphenol

The addition of a fluorine atom, on the other hand, could have a more complex effect. Fluorine is highly electronegative and introduces intermolecular dipole-dipole interactions. These interactions usually raise the melting point significantly, perhaps by +10°C. However, the positioning of the fluorine at the para position relative to the hydroxyl group may create intramolecular hydrogen bonding to fluorine, which could reduce intermolecular hydrogen bonding that is crucial for the high melting point of phenol. This intramolecular bonding could counteract the effects of increased intermolecular forces to some extent, so we might estimate a smaller increase due to fluorine, say of around +3°C.
